This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring May 2010 as Older Americans Month. The proclamation recognizes the contributions of older Americans to the nation and emphasizes the importance of supporting and appreciating them. The theme for this year's Older Americans Month is "Age Strong, Live Long," which acknowledges the efforts of people of all ages to promote the well-being, community involvement, and independence of senior citizens. The proclamation also highlights the government's commitment to strengthening Medicare and Medicaid, protecting Social Security, and providing preventive care and support for seniors. Additionally, it mentions efforts to prevent elder abuse and expand programs to fight fraud, waste, and abuse in healthcare. The proclamation concludes by calling upon citizens to honor older Americans during the month of May.